'''Complex equality''' is a theory of [[justice]] outlined by [[Michael Walzer]] in his 1983 work ''[[Spheres of Justice]]''. The theory posits that inequalities in the several spheres of society should not invade one another.{{sfn|Browning|1997|p=142}} Walzer's definition of complex equality is: "In formal terms, complex equality means that no citizen's standing in one sphere or with regard to one social good can be undercut by his standing in some other sphere, with regard to some other good."{{sfn|Walzer|1983|p=19}} __NOTOC__ ==See also== {{Portal|Ethics|Social and political philosophy}} * [[Equality of opportunity]]
